many others. Compounds coined in the U.S. are for instance &quot;&quot;foothill, landslide&quot;&quot; (in all senses), &quot;&quot;, teenager, brainstorm, , hitchhike, smalltime, and a huge number of others. Some are euphemistic &quot;&quot;(human resources, affirmative action, correctional facility).&quot;&quot; Many compound nouns have the verb-and-preposition combination: &quot;&quot;stopover, lineup, tryout, spin-off, shootout, holdup, hideout, comeback, makeover,&quot;&quot; and many more. Some prepositional and phrasal verbs are in fact of American origin (&quot;&quot;win out, hold up, back up/off/down/out, face up to&quot;&quot; and many others). Noun endings such as &quot;&quot;-ee (retiree), -ery (bakery), -ster (gangster)&quot;&quot; and &quot;&quot;-cian (beautician)&quot;&quot; are also particularly productive in the U.S. Several verbs</data>
